annotation.TEXT: Werther’s Originals are a rich caramel-flavored candy sold in grocery stores around the country.
“Keep on truckin’” was a slogan coined by underground cartoonist Robert “R.” Crumb in 1968; it was popular throughout the ‘70s.
An imitation of noises made by the Three Stooges comedy troupe, most commonly Curly Howard.
“Mahler’s Tenth” is a reference to Symphony No. 10 in F-sharp Major by composer Gustav Mahler.
Luther Vandross was one of the premier R&B artists of the ‘80s.
Ron Popeil is an inventor and infomercial mainstay who founded the company Ronco.
Zebulon “Grandpa” Walton was a character on the TV show The Waltons. He was played by Will Geer until Geer’s death in 1978.
The Maverick, which Jodie is in fact driving, was one of Ford’s most successful cars, made from 1970-77.
Ryan O’Neal became a ‘70s heartthrob thanks to Love Story, in which he and Ali McGraw played a doomed couple.
Some varieties of the OTC cough syrup Robitussin contain dextromethorphan, which can act as a hallucinogen and relaxant and is sometimes abused by teens.
Eye of newt is an ingredient in witches’ brews, as in Macbeth: “Eye of newt, and toe of frog/Wool of bat, and tongue of dog.”
“Sister Golden Hair” is a 1975 song by the folk rock band America; it was their second number one hit.
In real life, Robert Easton was a respected Hollywood dialect coach who was known as “The Man of a Thousand Voices.”
A reference to the old joke: “Why did the chicken cross the road? To get to the other side.”
Grape Nehi is a purple, grape-flavored soda manufactured by Royal Crown.
Sigourney Weaver is an actress who is best known for playing Ellen Ripley in the popular Alien horror movies.
Franz Schubert was an Austrian composer during the transition period from Classical to Romantic music. He is known especially for his lieder (songs).
Hallmark Hall of Fame is an anthology drama series that has aired off and on since 1951. It specializes in deeply wholesome, classic dramas.
On the TV show Seinfeld, Cosmo Kramer was the tall, lanky neighbor known for his dramatic entrances.
Monte Markham has appeared in dozens of movies and TV shows, including Baywatch and The Golden Girls.
A reference to MST3K Episode 810, The Giant Spider Invasion. Actor Robert Easton, who plays the lynch mob leader here, played alcoholic farmer Kester in that film.
Gloria Stuart played the heroine Rose as an old woman in the film Titanic.
Every Tuesday and Thursday, the Today show’s Willard Scott wishes happy birthdays to centenarians, referring to them as “100 years young.”
The role was played by Charlotte Greenwood.
Actress Edie Sedgwick appeared in several of Andy Warhol’s films. She once created a fuss by setting her room at the Chelsea Hotel on fire.
Palmolive liquid soap began using the slogan “Palmolive softens hands while you do the dishes” in the ‘60s.
The two devils Screwtape and Wormwood are the central characters in C.S. Lewis’s novel The Screwtape Letters.
Marilyn Manson is a shock rocker popular in the ‘90s, known for his religious imagery, androgyny, and elaborate makeup.
Until 2012 the immense discount-store chain hired retired seniors as “greeters”: employees who stand at the front entrance and welcome customers to the store.
A paraphrase of the 1978 Rush song “The Trees.”
Allegra is an OTC allergy medicine.
A paraphrase of the song “Sunrise, Sunset” from the Broadway musical Fiddler on the Roof.
Morley Safer has been a correspondent on the TV news program 60 Minutes since 1970.
A line from the song “Witchcraft” by Frank Sinatra.
The Necronomicon is a fictional book in the stories of H.P. Lovecraft. He described it as a history of the Old Ones and a way to summon them.
Neil Young is an influential singer/songwriter who played with the band Crosby, Stills, Nash & Young and the garage-rock band Crazy Horse.
Ed Ames (of the Ames Brothers band) played the Cherokee Mingo on the TV series Daniel Boone.
Now for your viewing pleasure…the fully annotated The Touch of Satan
Cecilia Bartoli is an Italian soprano who is considered one of the leading lights of the operatic world.
In the Old Testament, Beelzebub is the name given to the god worshiped by the Philistine city Ekron.
Ramen is a Chinese-style noodle popular in Japan. Instant ramen was first marketed in North America in the ‘70s and became a staple of poor college students.
Bigfoot is a legendary apelike creature that supposedly haunts the forests of the Pacific Northwest.
Kali is the Hindu goddess of destruction, usually depicted brandishing weapons and wearing a necklace of skulls.
Hollywood composer Mike Post has written music for dozens of TV shows.
Sock monkeys became popular in the 1930s. They are stuffed animals that can be made with a pair of Rockford Red Heel socks made by Fox River Mills.
It’s a myth that the Amish shun all buttons. They allow plain buttons, but nothing that would draw attention, like brass.
Actress Anne Heche dated comedian Ellen DeGeneres from 1997-2000.
“You’ll do your thing and I’ll do mine” is a paraphrase of the “Gestalt Prayer,” which was written by therapist Fritz Perls and became popular during the ‘70s.
Madeline, a young schoolgirl in Paris, is the main character in a series of children’s books by Ludwig Bemelmans.
Christopher Atkins became a teen heartthrob thanks to The Blue Lagoon, in which he and Brooke Shields played two children who grow up and fall in love on a desert island.
Paula Cole is a singer-songwriter of the Tori Amos/Sarah McLachlan school.
Lend Me a Tenor is a Broadway farce about a missing opera singer that is extremely popular with community theater groups.
“Amazing Grace” is an English hymn that became hugely popular in America during the Second Great Awakening of the early 19th century.
Watergate is a reference to the burglary at the Watergate Hotel that ultimately forced President Richard M. Nixon to resign in 1974.
If we missed any reference, be sure to let us know in the comments!
A Möbius strip is a length of paper that is given a half-twist and joined at the ends, which makes it a surface with only one side. It is named after its discoverer, A.F. Möbius.
J. Edgar Hoover (1895-1972) was the director of the FBI for decades. In 1993, author Anthony Summers claimed he was a cross-dresser.
Richard Carpenter was half of The Carpenters, along with his sister Karen. They released a string of soft-rock hits in the early ‘70s.
In a 1976 ad for Peter Pan peanut butter, a group of children at first refuse to believe in peanut butter. A cartoon Peter Pan convinces them.
The Adam Sandler film The Wedding Singer contains a famous scene in which a little old lady (played by Ellen Albertini Dow) raps at a wedding.
Amazing Grace and Chuck is a film about a young boy who inspires pro athletes to strike for nuclear disarmament.
Ron Palillo was best known for playing Arnold Horshack on the TV show Welcome Back, Kotter.
A reference to MST3K Episode 806, The Undead.
This seems to be a general reference to those dolls that simulate eating, crying, wetting their diapers, and other joys of motherhood.
Mavericks were so popular that they out-sold the classic Ford Mustang.
The 1970s saw an oil embargo by OPEC and the revolution in Iran, which led to skyrocketing gas prices and shortages.
Edgar Winter is an albino blues/rock musician. His best-known song is 1973’s “Frankenstein.”
Flash paper is a special paper used by stage magicians that flares brightly, burns quickly, and leaves no ashes behind.
Irving “Swifty” Lazar was a legendary Hollywood agent known for his spectacular post-Oscar parties.
Jesuits are members of the Society of Jesus, a Catholic religious order. The priest in The Exorcist was a Jesuit.
Character actor Clu Gulager has appeared in dozens of movies and TV shows.
Igor Stravinsky was one of the founders of modernist music and one of the most important composers of the 20th century.
Steinlager is a New Zealand beer. Pete’s Wicked Ale was a hugely popular microbrew in the ‘90s, but it ceased production in 2011.
Eric “Hoss” Cartwright (Dan Blocker) was one of the sons on the TV western Bonanza.
The Village People were a campy disco group that wore costumes: Indian, cowboy, biker, soldier, construction worker, and policeman.
Dolls with heads made from carved, dried apples are a traditional American folk craft.
“Cluitie” is an old Scottish name for the devil; one source says it is a reference to the devil’s cloven hooves.
Oliver Hardy was the bossy, fussy half of the comedy team Laurel & Hardy, opposite Stan Laurel’s gentle incompetent.
In Christian mythology, Lucifer was the name of Satan before he rebelled and fell from heaven.
These are lyrics to the song “Melissa” by the Allman Brothers Band.
Get the scoop about every reference in the film. Even the silly ones.
Comedian David Spade was a regular on Saturday Night Live and later acted in a number of movies with fellow SNL alum Chris Farley.
Kabuki is a traditional form of Japanese theater in which the actors wear thick, dramatic makeup.
The poem “The Village Blacksmith” by Henry Wadsworth Longfellow opens with the lines “Under a spreading chestnut tree/The village smithy stands ...”
Teen idol David Cassidy played Keith Partridge on the ‘70s TV series The Partridge Family.
Tanglewood is the summer concert home of the Boston Symphony Orchestra.
The Prairie League was an independent baseball league in parts of Canada and the Upper Midwest; it ceased operations in 1997.
A paraphrase of a traditional camp song found under several names: “Juvenile Delinquent,” “I Want a Man,” “The Farmer and the Maiden,” etc.
Family Affair starred Brian Keith as Bill Davis, a swinging bachelor who had to take care of his brother’s orphaned children.
“Squarehead” is a slur typically directed at Germanic and Scandinavian immigrants, dating to the late 19th century. It was primarily used in the Upper Midwest.
A paraphrase of the song “I’ll Never Fall in Love Again” by Burt Bacharach & Hal David.
The Green Bay Packers are a pro football team out of Green Bay, Wisconsin.
William McKinley was the 25th president of the United States. He was shot by an anarchist on Sept. 5, 1901, dying 9 days later.
In 1994 Pepsi launched a major ad campaign centered on “freshness dating” its soft drinks.
In the New Testament, Beelzebub is referred to as the prince of demons.
Captain Hook was the villainous pirate in J.M. Barrie’s classic kids’ tale Peter Pan. Smee was his sidekick.
The Rainbow Gathering began in 1972 and still continues: a bunch of people meeting in a U.S. National Forest and conducting a group meditation.
Mid-‘90s TV ads for 3M/Scotch brand window insulation kits featured a guy in a Scottish kilt.
In the same Monty Python skit, the composer bitterly says he’s going to get rid of the shed, and the interviewer points out that would make him Arthur “No Sheds” Jackson.
Sustacal is a liquid nutritional supplement similar to Ensure, but marketed primarily to seniors.
Sudafed is an over-the-counter decongestant.
Lake Wobegon is a fictional town in Minnesota created by NPR mainstay Garrison Keillor, who has been telling stories about it on A Prairie Home Companion since the ‘70s.
Welcome Back, Kotter (1975-79) starred Gabe Kaplan as a teacher in a Brooklyn high school.
The Michigan Militia was a paramilitary, anti-government group in the 1990s. It was almost defunct by 2000, but after Obama’s election in 2008 it began to grow again.
An imitation of Don Knotts as Barney Fife, the hapless deputy sheriff on The Andy Griffith Show.
Devil’s food cake is a classic chocolate cake recipe. It usually uses cocoa and boiling water instead of chocolate and milk.
Kinko’s was a national chain of photocopying stores. In 2004 FedEx bought it and renamed it FedEx Office.
If we missed any, let us know in the comments.
Gymboree is a chain of activity centers that offer play, music, and art classes for kids ages 0-5.
The Grant Wood painting American Gothic shows a man and woman in front of a Midwestern farmhouse, the man holding a pitchfork.
Jean “Toots” Thielemans is a Belgian harmonica player who has played with most of the famous names in jazz.
Actor Lee Amber resembles conductor Leonard Bernstein, who studied and worked at Tanglewood.
Anthony Zerbe is a character actor known for villainous roles in ‘70s films like The Omega Man.
Gas stations sometimes gave out glasses with pictures of sports stars (like L.A. Rams quarterback Roman Gabriel) with your gas purchase.
In the ‘70s, a rumor arose that P&G’s logo—the man in the moon surrounded by 13 stars—was a satanic symbol. The company was finally forced to retire the logo in 1985.

The Touch of Satan: Fully annotated by The Official MST3K YouTube Channel.
Don't forget to tell us if we missed any references!
John Quincy Adams was the sixth president of the United States (1825-29).
In the film Titanic, Kate Winslet is sitting in front of a mirror when her fiancé (Billy Zane) gives her a priceless necklace called the Coeur de la Mer (Heart of the Ocean).
Lurch was the name of the harpsichord-playing butler on the TV series The Addams Family; the part was played by Ted Cassidy.
Rhoda was a ‘70s sitcom starring Valerie Harper. It was a spinoff of The Mary Tyler Moore Show, where Harper played Rhoda for four years.
Hardrock, Coco and Joe is a Christmas short about three elves who help Santa deliver his presents.
Tony Musante starred in the 1973 detective show Toma, which became Baretta after Musante left the show.
Michael Eisner was the CEO of Disney from 1984-2005, and for two decades one of the richest and most powerful men in Hollywood.
Since 1995, when students in Le Sueur, MN, found a batch of deformed frogs, similar frogs have been found in 75% of Minnesota’s counties. The cause is still unknown.
Don “The Snake” Prudhomme was a legendary drag racer during the ‘70s & ‘80s.
Wicca priestess and author Margot Adler was an NPR correspondent from 1979 until her death in 2014.
Eddie Munster was the young son on the TV series The Munsters. He was played by Butch Patrick.
We hope you enjoyed the fully-annotated The Touch of Satan
A reference to the classic children’s book The Very Lonely Firefly by Eric Carle.
“Whip inflation now” was a slogan launched by President Gerald Ford’s administration in the ‘70s to boost public confidence in an era of rising prices.
Leatherface, played by Gunnar Hansen, was the villain in the classic horror film The Texas Chain Saw Massacre.
Hieronymous Bosch was a Dutch artist known for surreal paintings filled with fantastical creatures.
In 1966, John Lennon quipped that the Beatles were more popular than Jesus; conservative Christians in the U.S. burned their records in retaliation.
Herbal Essences is a line of shampoos, conditioners, hairsprays and so on. Irish Spring is a deodorant soap introduced in 1972.
In a classic Monty Python skit, an interviewer drives composer Arthur “Two Sheds” Jackson into despair by asking about his nickname, not his music.
Friedrich “Fritz” Kreisler was an Austrian composer who is considered one of the greatest violinists of all time.
Streaking was a popular fad during the ‘70s, consisting of a young man taking off all his clothes and running very fast through some public place.
Jody and Buffy were the two young twins on the TV show Family Affair. (The third child was named Cissy.)
In the road game Punch Bug, the first child to spot a Volkswagen Beetle and shout “Punch bug!” gets to punch the other kids in the car.
Eubie Blake was a ragtime musician who wrote the musical Shuffle Along.
With annotations provided by The Annotated MST website.
An imitation of many, many ‘70s soundtracks, with the iconic example being Isaac Hayes’ “Theme from Shaft.”
Ernest and Julio Gallo are major winemakers, with an enormous winery in Modesto, CA.
President Gerald Ford got a reputation for being clumsy after a few on-camera incidents, which was reinforced by Chevy Chase’s parody of him on SNL.
“Engine run-on” or “dieseling” occurs when a hotspot in a vehicle’s engine continues to ignite gas after the ignition has been turned off.
An Iron Maiden was a likely fictional instrument of torture: a box crudely shaped like a human being and lined on the inside of the doors with spikes.
The 1996 film Fled chained good actor Laurence Fishburne to mediocre actor Stephen Baldwin. The two played escaped convicts on the run from the law.
The L.A. Police Department got a reputation for extreme violence after four officers were videotaped viciously beating a man named Rodney King in 1991.
Gulager can be seen in two MST3K episodes: 322, Master Ninja I, and 614, San Francisco International.
In the films Pulp Fiction and Point of No Return, Harvey Keitel played a “cleaner,” a person who is called in to dispose of inconvenient corpses.
Ostensibly a line from the Star Trek episode “This Side of Paradise,” the writers were shocked on viewing the show to realize Spock never actually says it.
A variation on the deodorant’s longtime ad slogan: “So effective you can skip a day.”
Poopdeck Pappy was Popeye’s father in the comic strip and animated cartoons by the same name.
Strom Thurmond (R-SC) served in the U.S. Senate from 1954-2003. He retired at the age of 100 and died 6 months later.
Mid-‘90s TV ads for Keystone Light beer featured an ugly guy suffering from “bitter beer face.”
The Bold Ones was a collection of rotating TV shows that ran from 1969-73: The New Doctors, The Lawyers, The Protectors, and The Senator.
Mr. Pibb was a soft drink made by the Coca-Cola Company to compete with Dr Pepper. It is now called Pibb Xtra.
“When _____ pain strikes” is a common phrase in many ads for pain relief products, particularly for the Tylenol drug family.
In 1996, Kelsey Grammer (Cheers, Frasier) flipped his car while driving under the influence; he has had a history of issues with drug and alcohol dependence.
Herbert von Karajan was a controversial conductor who insisted on polished perfection in his orchestra. He led the Berlin Philharmonic for 35 years.
“What's on the spit?” is a line from the 1972 film Jeremiah Johnson, starring Robert Redford as the mountain man.
Wide-wale corduroy pants, in which the raised lines on the fabric are wider than usual, were very popular in the ‘70s.
The Big Valley was a TV series starring Barbara Stanwyck as the head of a ranch in 1870s California.
An imitation of the folksy narrator (country musician Waylon Jennings) from the TV series The Dukes of Hazzard.
Scrabble is a classic board game in which players attempt to spell words on the board, crossword puzzle-style.
“Seniors cannot be turned down” appears to be a popular slogan in the insurance industry.
